  "prompt": "When does a Senate motion require 3/5 vote?",
  "response": "A motion in the U.S. Senate typically requires a 3/5 (60-vote) supermajority under the following circumstances:\n\n1. **Invoking Cloture**: The most common scenario is when the Senate seeks to end a filibuster and move to a final vote on a bill, nomination, or other matter. Under **Senate Rule XXII**, a cloture motion requires a 3/5 majority (60 votes if all 100 senators are present) to pass. Once cloture is invoked, debate is limited, and the Senate can proceed to a final vote.\n\n2. **Waiving Budget Reconciliation Rules**: During the budget reconciliation process, certain provisions may be subject to a point of order under the **Byrd Rule**. To waive such a point of order, a 3/5 majority vote is required in most cases.\n\n3. **Overriding a Presidential Veto**: While overriding a presidential veto requires a 2/3 majority in both the House and Senate, this is a distinct scenario from the 3/5 threshold, which is more commonly associated with cloture and filibusters.\n\nIt\u2019s important to note that the 3/5 threshold is not universally required for all Senate actions. Most Senate business, including regular legislation and confirmations, requires only a simple majority (51 votes) unless a filibuster is in play, in which case cloture must be invoked with 60 votes. However, exceptions exist, such as in the case of budget reconciliation or certain procedural rules.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
